## CDN Architecture — Edge Computing at Scale

### The Physics of Global Content Delivery

Without CDN:
```
Sydney user -> US-East origin (280ms RTT)
Total for 2MB image: 280ms (TCP) + 280ms (TLS) + transfer time
= ~600ms to first byte + download time
```

With CDN (cache hit):
```
Sydney user -> Sydney CDN edge (10ms RTT)
Total: 10ms to first byte + download time (local bandwidth)
```

With CDN (cache miss):
```
Sydney user -> Sydney edge (10ms) -> US-East origin (280ms) -> Sydney edge -> User
Total: ~590ms — similar to no CDN, but subsequent requests are cached
```

**CDN effectiveness** = cache hit rate × (latency savings per hit). At 95% hit rate and 270ms savings per hit = 256ms average latency reduction.

### Cache-Control Headers — The Complete Guide

```typescript
import express from "express";
import path from "path";

const app = express();

// Static assets with content hash in filename (e.g., main.a3f2c1.js)
// Cache forever — filename changes when content changes
app.use("/static", express.static("dist", {
  setHeaders: (res, filePath) => {
    if (/\.[0-9a-f]{8}\.(js|css|woff2?)$/.test(filePath)) {
      res.set("Cache-Control", "public, max-age=31536000, immutable");
      // immutable: tells browser not to revalidate — saves conditional GET requests
    }
  },
}));

// HTML files — never cache (they reference hashed assets)
app.get("/*.html", (req, res, next) => {
  res.set("Cache-Control", "no-cache"); // revalidate on every request
  next();
});

// API: fresh for 5 min, serve stale for 1 min while revalidating in background
app.get("/api/products", async (req, res) => {
  const products = await getProducts();
  res.set("Cache-Control", "public, max-age=300, stale-while-revalidate=60");
  // stale-while-revalidate: CDN serves cached response immediately
  // while asynchronously fetching fresh content for the next request
  res.json(products);
});

// Vary header: CDN must cache separate versions per Accept-Encoding
app.get("/api/data", async (req, res) => {
  res.set("Vary", "Accept-Encoding, Accept-Language");
  // WARNING: each Vary value multiplies CDN cache entries
  // Vary: User-Agent = disaster (thousands of cache entries per URL)
  res.json(await getData());
});
```

### Origin Shield

Without origin shield: each of 285 CDN POPs may independently miss the cache and hit your origin — up to 285 simultaneous requests for the same uncached URL.

With origin shield: all edges check a single designated shield POP first. If the shield misses, only the shield calls origin — reducing origin load by up to 285x.

```mermaid
graph TD
    SYD["Sydney Edge"] --> Shield["Shield POP<br/>(e.g., US-East)"] 
    TYO["Tokyo Edge"] --> Shield
    FRA["Frankfurt Edge"] --> Shield
    LAX["Los Angeles Edge"] --> Shield
    Shield --> Origin["Origin Server"]
    style Shield fill:#e67e22,color:#fff
    style Origin fill:#e74c3c,color:#fff
```

### CDN for APIs — Edge Caching Patterns

```python
from functools import wraps
import hashlib

def cdn_cacheable(ttl: int = 300, stale: int = 60, vary: list = None):
    def decorator(func):
        @wraps(func)
        async def wrapper(request, response, *args, **kwargs):
            result = await func(request, response, *args, **kwargs)
            vary_headers = vary or ["Accept-Encoding"]
            response.headers["Cache-Control"] = (
                f"public, max-age={ttl}, stale-while-revalidate={stale}"
            )
            response.headers["Vary"] = ", ".join(vary_headers)
            # Surrogate-Key for targeted purge (Fastly/Varnish)
            surrogate_keys = " ".join([f"endpoint:{func.__name__}"])
            response.headers["Surrogate-Key"] = surrogate_keys
            return result
        return wrapper
    return decorator

async def purge_cdn_by_tag(tag: str, fastly_service_id: str, fastly_key: str):
    import httpx
    async with httpx.AsyncClient() as client:
        response = await client.post(
            f"https://api.fastly.com/service/{fastly_service_id}/purge/{tag}",
            headers={"Fastly-Key": fastly_key},
        )
    return response.status_code == 200

# On product update, purge all CDN caches tagged with that product
async def update_product(product_id: str, data: dict):
    await db.update("products", product_id, data)
    await purge_cdn_by_tag(f"product:{product_id}", FASTLY_SERVICE_ID, FASTLY_KEY)
```

### CDN Metrics to Monitor

| Metric | Target | Alert If |
|--------|--------|----------|
| Cache Hit Ratio | > 90% | < 70% for 5+ minutes |
| Origin Error Rate | < 0.1% | > 1% |
| Edge Latency p99 | < 50ms | > 200ms |
| Cache Fill Rate | < 5% of requests | > 20% (cold cache) |
| Bandwidth Offload | > 85% | < 60% |

## Interview Q&A

**Q: Can you cache authenticated API responses on a CDN?**
A: Yes, with care. Options: (1) Cache public parts of the response, fetch personalised parts client-side. (2) Cache per-user with user ID in cache key — but this defeats the purpose (1:1 cache:user). (3) Edge-side includes (ESI): CDN assembles response from cached fragments + dynamic fragments. (4) For truly private data: do not cache on CDN, cache at origin (Redis).

**Q: What is the thundering herd problem for CDN cache expiry?**
A: When a popular item's TTL expires, thousands of requests simultaneously hit origin. Solutions: (1) Staggered TTLs (add random offset to TTL). (2) stale-while-revalidate (serve stale, revalidate async). (3) Cache lock at origin shield (only one refill request per item). (4) Predictive refresh: refresh before expiry based on popularity.

**Q: How do you handle CDN cache for A/B tests?**
A: Use separate cache keys per variant: Vary on a cookie or query parameter containing the variant ID. Or better: run A/B test entirely at the edge using CDN workers (Cloudflare Workers, Lambda@Edge) — no origin hit needed for variant selection.

